    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-28T15:00:00-05:00" n="890"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d890">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.628/147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 28, 1936—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. Embassy’s despatch No. 1558, November 20, 1935.<note n="90" xml:id="d890fn90"
                        >Not printed; see telegram No. 208, November 12, 1935, 5 p.m., from the
                        Chargé in Japan, <ref target="frus1935v03#pg_1078">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1935, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>,
                            p. 1078</ref>.</note> The Department of Commerce has received reports
                    from unofficial sources <pb facs="1038" n="943" xml:id="pg_943"/> that Japanese
                    vessels have obtained licenses for salmon fishing in waters adjacent to Alaska
                    and are now engaged in such fishing. It is believed that circulation of such
                    reports might most effectively be discouraged by the Department of Commerce
                    making known to Alaskan salmon fishery interests the assurances given to you
                    last year by the Foreign Office as reported in your despatch above cited.</p>
                <p>Please communicate the foregoing to the Foreign Office and inquire whether there
                    would be objection to the procedure above outlined, reporting reply of the
                    Foreign Office promptly by telegraph.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
